  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, US)\n- First international anti-money laundering guidelines\n- Limited scope and enforcement\n\n2. 1980s-1990s Developments\n- FATF (Financial Action Task Force) established in 1989\n- Increased international cooperation\n- More comprehensive regulatory frameworks\n- Enhanced reporting requirements for financial institutions\n\n3. Post-9/11 Legislation\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Stricter identification and transaction monitoring rules\n- Expanded definitions of money laundering\n- Enhanced global counterterrorism financing regulations\n\n4. Recent Trends\n- Digital currency regulations\n- Cryptocurrency transaction tracking\n- Enhanced beneficial ownership transparency\n- Cross-border information sharing\n- Expanded Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n\n5. Technological Advancements\n- AI and machine learning for transaction monitoring\n- Blockchain tracking capabilities\n- Advanced risk assessment algorithms\n- Real-time suspicious activity detection\n\n6. Current Focus\n- Comprehensive beneficial ownership registries\n- Stricter corporate transparency requirements\n- Enhanced international collaboration\n- Adapting to emerging digital financial technologies\n\nThe legislation continues to evolve, becoming more sophisticated and comprehensive.",
